did.head: Papers Summary
did.abstract: The William Carey Crane papers contain personal correspondence, financial documents, legal documents, literary productions, and photographic materials belonging to the former president of Baylor University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The William Carey Crane papers being in 1809 and end in 1944, but the bulk of the materials originated during William Carey Crane’s prestigious career as pastor and educator (1834-1885). Many materials are general correspondence and literary productions, but the collection also includes personal correspondence, family correspondence, legal documents, financial documents, and photographic materials.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The current organization of the William Carey Crane papers has gone through significant changes prior to this finding aid. Currently the records are arranged in seven series: I. General Correspondence, II. Personal Correspondence, III. Family Correspondence, IV. Legal Documents, V. Financial Documents, VI. Literary Productions, and VII. Photographic Materials. Series I and VI comprise the bulk of the collection.

accessrestrict.p: All requests for copying of materials must be submitted to The Texas Collection in writing. Please use the Request Form for Copying Materials sheet. Archivist''s Notes: Ask the archivist for an index of William Carey Crane’s correspondence, found in the control file for this collection. While the letters have been reorganized since the index was created, it will give the researcher an idea of the contents.

A tracer can be found in the control file that directs the researcher to explore the Lewis R. Bryan Items collection. In this collection, there is a speech given by Mr. Bryan concerning William Carey Crane.
In addition to the control file, there is a folder containing an index of Crane’s book collection and an essay written by James M. Davis concerning William Carey Crane’s views of slavery.

Within the Literary Productions series, the researcher can find significant amounts of biographical materials pertaining to General Sam Houston, including an early copy of a letter sent by Houston to his friend, President Andrew Jackson. Crane collected these materials in the hopes of writing a biography about Houston. His final work, Life and Select Literary Remains of Sam Houston of Texas, was published by J.B. Lippincott & Company out of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, in 1884. This book is available at The Texas Collection.
The following list of individuals contains William Carey Crane’s family members who are identified within this collection. The individual’s relationship to Crane follows the name.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series, the largest in the collection, contains William Carey Crane’s correspondence about Baylor University, the Civil War, and Baptists in Texas.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series contains William Carey Crane’s correspondence with various individuals, universities, and conventions.
